enumerations.name: ArgumentDirectionEnum
enumerations.note: Use cases: • Arguments in ClientServerOperation can have different directions that need to be formally indicated because they have an impact on how the function signature looks like eventually. • Arguments in BswModuleEntry already determine a function signature, but the direction is used to specify the semantics, especially of pointer arguments. Aggregated by ArgumentDataPrototype.direction, SwServiceArg.direction

literals.name: in
literals.description:
The argument value is passed to the callee.
Tags: atp.EnumerationLiteralIndex=0

literals.name: inout
literals.description:
The argument value is passed to the callee but also passed back from the callee to the caller.
Tags: atp.EnumerationLiteralIndex=1

literals.name: out
literals.description:
The argument value is passed from the callee to the caller.
Tags: atp.EnumerationLiteralIndex=2

enumerations.name: ByteOrderEnum
enumerations.note: When more than one byte is stored in the memory the order of those bytes may differ depending on the architecture of the processing unit. If the least significant byte is stored at the lowest address, this architecture is called little endian and otherwise it is called big endian. ByteOrder is very important in case of communication between different PUs or ECUs. Aggregated by ApSomeipTransformationProps.byteOrder, BaseTypeDirectDefinition.byteOrder, DiagnosticCommon Props.defaultEndianness, ISignalToIPduMapping.packingByteOrder, MultiplexedIPdu.selectorField ByteOrder, PduToFrameMapping.packingByteOrder, SegmentPosition.segmentByteOrder, SOMEIP TransformationDescription.byteOrder, System.containerIPduHeaderByteOrder

literals.name: decreasing
literals.description:
This indicates that the related curve needs to be monotony decreasing.

literals.name: increasing
literals.description:
This indicates that the related curve needs to be monotony increasing.
Tags: atp.EnumerationLiteralIndex=1

literals.name: monotonous
literals.description:
This indicates that the values shall be monotonously decreasing or increasing, depending on the trend set by the first values of the series.

literals.name: noMonotony
literals.description:

literals.name: strictlyDecreasing

literals.name: strictlyIncreasing

literals.name: strictMonotonous
